\begin_layout Section*
Q1
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Construct a non-ergodic training dataset,
 consisting of Mess3 processes with different parameters,
 where each training sequence is generated entirely by one Mess3 ergodic component.
 Train a transformer on this data via next-token prediction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Please see the code at the 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "repository"
target "https://github.com/japhba/mats-simplex-2026"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Why do you think this type of structure is interesting and/or relevant to language models?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Language models are trained on a large number of documents of text.
 A possible mapping here is that every document can be thought of as a sample from a specific distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $P(x_{1:T}|c)$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is the context of the document (prose,
 law,
 poems,
 ...).
 Surely,
 even for large 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

,
 the sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1:T}$
\end_inset

 would not be ergodic for the marginalized distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $P(x_{1:T})=\sum_{c}P(x_{1:T}|c)P(c)$
\end_inset

.
 I think that even within a single context,
 ergodicity is typically not fulfilled.
 I think the basic problem is that 
\begin_inset Formula $P(x_{1:T}|c)$
\end_inset

 is not stationary,
 i.e.
 the continuation will be largely dependent on past utterance.
 This is a fundamental difficulty in language modeling that challenges classical approaches such as latent Dirichlet allocation that posit simpler stationary approaches with a limited number of latent factors.
 However,
 I think herein also lies the solution to make the link:
 in approximation,
 at least in terms of marginal statistics for a single token's 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{t}$
\end_inset

 frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $P(x_{t}|c)$
\end_inset

,
 natural language is well approximated by these sort of hidden Markov models.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Q2
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Make a pre-registered prediction (honor code) as to what geometry the activations should take,
 and how it should change with context position and across layers.
 Derive this prediction mathematically as far as you can,
 and separately give your intuition for what the geometry should look like.
 You will not be penalized for getting this wrong—
we are interested in both your formal reasoning and your geometric intuition.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The processes we consider here take the following form (using notation of the paper).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\text{emission-transitions } & P(s',x_{t}|s)=T_{ss'}^{(x_{t})}\\
\text{marginalized stationary (latent) transitions} & \sum_{x_{t}}P(s',x_{t}|s)=P(s'|s)=T_{ss'}\\
\text{hidden state distribution } & P(s_{t}|x_{:t})=\beta_{t}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A priori,
 there is multiple implementations that an arbitrarily expressive predictor (i.e.
 one that is Bayes-optimal) may assume,
 and it is not even clear that within the class of transformer models these implementations will the same.
 However,
 it is somewhat generally assumed that neural networks have simplicity biases,
 i.e.
 implement a solution that is in some way compact (requires the least amount of parameters/has small parameter norm).
 For this process,
 we can consider two alternative hypotheses:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
1.
 The transformer memorizes the entire set of observation dependent transitions 
\begin_inset Formula $\{T_{ss'}^{(x_{t})}\}_{x_{t}}$
\end_inset

.
 This comes at a memory cost 
\begin_inset Formula $|\mathcal{X}||\mathcal{S}|^{2}$
\end_inset

,
 and requires indexing into this set to retrieve the required transition matrix.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2.
 The transformer only models latent transitions.
 This drastically reduces the memory cost to 
\begin_inset Formula $|\mathcal{S}|^{2}$
\end_inset

,
 but now requires forwarding the latent dynamics and then emitting.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2) here seems the more plausible outcome from the perspective of simplicity and memory efficiency.
 In particular,
 we can adopt a (linear) dynamical systems perspective that models this directly.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
A single-head,
 linear attention operation on the residual stream 
\begin_inset Formula $\bh_{t}^{\ell}$
\end_inset

 in layer 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 reads
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bh_{t}^{\ell}=\sum_{t'}a_{tt'}\bh_{t'}^{\l}=\sum_{t'}(W_{Q}\bh_{t}^{\l})^{\T}(W_{K}\bh_{t'}^{\l})\bh_{t'}^{\l}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
For the choice of 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{Q}W_{K}=T$
\end_inset

 and an appropriate partitioning 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{t}=[1,\ldots,1,\beta_{t}]$
\end_inset

 ,
 attention can implement the latent state transition if we identify some part of 
\begin_inset Formula $\bh_{t}^{\l}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 A context-dependent transition can be achieved by multi-head attention,
 with contexts indexing into heads via a one-hot encoding of context in 
\begin_inset Formula $\bh_{t}^{\l}$
\end_inset

.
 Explicitly,
 construct the attention weights as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
W_{Q}=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
T & 0\\
0 & 0
\end{array}\right],\quad W_{K}=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
\I & 0\\
0 & 0
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
and thus
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(W_{Q}\bh_{t}^{\l})^{\T}(W_{K}\bh_{t'}^{\l})=\left[\begin{array}{c}
\be_{\eta_{t}}\\
\eta_{t}
\end{array}\right]^{\T}\left[\begin{array}{cc}
T & 0\\
0 & 0
\end{array}\right]^{\T}\left[\begin{array}{cc}
\I & 0\\
0 & 0
\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{c}
\be_{\eta_{t'}}\\
\eta_{t}
\end{array}\right]=\be_{t}^{\T}T\be_{t'}=T_{tt'}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
So the transformer needs to do two tasks:
 1) track the latent state 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{t}$
\end_inset

 as a one-hot encoding in the residual stream
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
2) can be implemented easily in a transformer by constructing a matrix multiply 
\begin_inset Formula $W\coloneqq T$
\end_inset

 somewhere in the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

vertical
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (i.e.,
 the layer stack) forward pass of the transformer.
 In particular,
 the following minimal 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

transformer
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 model would propogate a distribution.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\bx_{t}$
\end_inset

 denote the tokenized input,
 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{E}$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{UE}$
\end_inset

 be the embedding/unembedding matrices.
 Then,
 initialize 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bx_{0}\coloneqq W_{E}^{-1}\beta_{0},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
adopt an identity attention operation,
 and a single-layer MLP block of 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{\text{MLP}}\coloneqq\bT-\I$
\end_inset

,
 and choose 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{UE}=W_{E}^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
A forward pass (logits) then read
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\bx_{1} & =\bW_{UE}\bW_{\text{MLP}}\bW_{E}\bx_{0}\\
 & =W_{UE}W_{\text{MLP}}W_{E}W_{E}^{-1}\beta_{0}\\
 & =\bW_{UE}T\beta_{0}\\
 & =\bW_{UE}\beta_{1}\\
 & =\bx_{1}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This simple argument has however made the approximation that latent and observation belief states are just related by a linear,
 invertable transform,
 which is not true generally.
 We can however fix this argument by saying that the first half of transformer layers will map 
\begin_inset Formula $\bx\rightarrow\eta$
\end_inset

,
 a 
\begin_inset Formula $\bW_{\text{MLP}}=T$
\end_inset

 layer does the forward of the latent state,
 and the latter half of the layer stack does the inverse mapping 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta\rightarrow x$
\end_inset

.
 If we furthermore restrict the model so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\bx$
\end_inset

 is actually one-hot instead of a distribution over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

,
 this task becomes more difficult.
 We now need to integrate the present inference into the latent inference by doing the belief state update 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\beta_{t}\leftarrow\sum_{s_{t-1}}P(x_{t}|s_{t})P(s_{t}|s_{t-1})\,P(s_{t-1})=\bT^{(x_{t})}\beta_{t-1}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\beta_{t+1}\leftarrow P(s_{t+1}|x_{t})=\sum_{s_{t}}P(s_{t+1}|x_{t},s_{t})P(s_{t}|x_{t})=P(s_{t+1},x_{t}|s_{t})/P(x_{t}|s_{t})\propto P(s_{t+1},x_{t}|s_{t})=T_{s_{t}s_{t+1}}^{(x_{t})}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Can we implement this with a transformer?
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\bT_{s_{t-1}s_{t}}^{(x_{t})}$
\end_inset

 depends on the previous latent and thus memory.
 We can try leveraging the attention to accomplish this:
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(W_{Q}x) & :\text{index into T}\\
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
keep T in forward pass
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
but we just load information into RS
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
so we need to get context,
 but ok
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
yeah but maybe we actually wanna do a scalar mult
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
use the log,
 Luke
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Optimal inference in transformer forward pass
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "par:Optimal-inference"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I would like to see if we can implement the inference operation for variant 2) in the transformer forward pass using weight-encoded ground truth knowledge of the world properties 
\begin_inset Formula $P(x_{t}|s{}_{t})$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $P(s'|s)$
\end_inset

,
 the following is my attempt at deriving such an implementation.
 To this end,
 suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\bx_{t}\equiv P(\bx_{t}|s_{t})\in\bR^{|\mathcal{X}|}$
\end_inset

 holds the belief over the observation space given the current latent belief.
 Furthermore,
 partition the first and second layer's residual stream (RS) into the axis-aligned direct sum 
\begin_inset Formula $\bh=\bR^{|\mathcal{S}|}\oplus\bR^{|\mathcal{X}|}\oplus\bR^{C}\oplus\bR^{d_{P}}$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 denotes the number of contexts (i.e.
 distinct stochastic processes) and 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{P}$
\end_inset

 is some positional embedding (I will only explicitly populate the 
\begin_inset Formula $\bR^{|\mathcal{S}|}\oplus\bR^{|\mathcal{X}|}$
\end_inset

 in the following for easier notation).
 I will denote this partitioning as 
\begin_inset Formula $\bh=[\bm{a},\,\bm{b}]$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{a}\in\bR^{|\mathcal{S}|},\,\bm{b}\in\bR^{|\mathcal{X}|}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\bx}_{t}\in\bR^{|\mathcal{X}|}$
\end_inset

 be the current one-hot encoded observation,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bx_{t}\in\bR^{|\mathcal{X}|}$
\end_inset

 a continuously-valued belief state on the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

-simplex.Then,
 the following steps should implement inference:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
1.
 Load observation into RS via embed,
 already logged by construction,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\bW_{E}=\I$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bh_{t}^{1}\coloneqq\bW_{E}\bx_{t}=[0,P(x_{t}|s{}_{t})]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2.
 Load last latent belief from the KV cache into the RS via attention
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\bh_{t}^{1} & =\bh_{t}^{1}+\sum_{t'}\left((\bW_{Q}^{1}\bh_{t}^{1})^{\T}(\bW_{K}^{1}\bh_{t'}^{1})\right)\bW_{V}^{1}\bm{h}_{t'}^{1}\\
 & =[\beta_{t},P(x_{t}|s{}_{t})],
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
which is achieved for 
\begin_inset Formula $\bW_{V}=\I$
\end_inset

 and having some addition (learned) positional embedding in 
\begin_inset Formula $\bh^{1}$
\end_inset

 and projections/shifts 
\begin_inset Formula $\bW_{Q},\text{\bW}_{K}$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\bW_{Q}\bh_{t}^{1})^{\T}(\bW_{K}\bh_{t'}^{1})=\delta_{t,t'+1},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
i.e.
 will will only load/add the last latent state belief into the RS.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
3.
 Forward s subspace by defining the MLP to just be a single layer matmul
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\bW_{\MLP}^{1}\coloneqq\bT-\I$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\bh^{1} & =\bh^{1}+\text{MLP}(\bh^{1})\\
 & =[\bT\beta_{t-1},P(x_{t}|\bs{}_{t})]\\
 & =[\beta_{t},P(x_{t}|\bs{}_{t})]
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
4.
 Combine with observation likelihood
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now need to combine the belief state with the observations.
 To that end,
 we first transform with another MLP to implement an elementwise 
\begin_inset Formula $\log$
\end_inset

 (this should at least approximatively be possible via universal approximation theorems),
 with a trivial attention operation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bh^{2}=\bh^{2}+\text{MLP}(\bh^{2})\eqqcolon[\log\beta_{t},\,\log P(x_{t}|\bs{}_{t})].
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then,
 just operate with another matmul 
\begin_inset Formula $\bW_{\MLP}^{3}=\left[\begin{array}{c}
\I\\
\I
\end{array}\right]-\I$
\end_inset

,
 giving (again with trivial attention)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\bh^{3} & =\bh^{2}+\bW_{\MLP}^{3}\text{\bh}^{2}\\
 & =\log\beta_{t}+\log P(x_{t}|\bs{}_{t})=\log\left(P(x_{t}|\bs{}_{t})\beta_{t}\right),
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where the multiplication in the last expression is an elementwise (Hadamard) multiplication.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This object is proportional matches the belief 
\begin_inset Formula $\log P(\bs_{t}|x_{:t+1}).$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
5.
 Undo logarithmic transform
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now,
 we can apply another MLP-transformation to undo the logarithm:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bh_{t}^{4}=P(x_{t}|\bs{}_{t})\beta_{t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
6.
 And finally,
 if we optionally are interested in probabilities in observation space,
 multiply with an unembedding matrix constructed as 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\bW_{UE}\right)_{x_{t}s_{t}}\coloneqq P(x_{t}|s_{t})$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bx_{t}=\bW_{UE}\bh_{t}^{4}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bh_{t}^{\ell}=\sum_{t'}(W_{Q}\bh_{t}^{\l})^{\T}(W_{K}\bh_{t'}^{\l})W_{V}\bm{x}_{t'}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\bh_{t}^{\ell} & =\sum_{t'}(W_{Q}\bh_{t}^{\l})^{\T}(W_{K}\bh_{t'}^{\l})W_{V}\bm{x}_{t'}\\
 & =\log P(s_{t}|s_{t-1})+\log P(x_{t}|s_{t}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This means that the residual stream should encode the belief state 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\bs_{t}|x_{1:t})$
\end_inset

 over the current latents given the observation history.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Implications for latent geometry
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If this is true,
 the different layers of the transformer should represent the different mapping stages from one-hot observations 
\begin_inset Formula $\bx_{t}$
\end_inset

 towards the belief states 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{t}$
\end_inset

 in deeper layers.
 The belief states themselves,
 in any given parameter context,
 would by ergodicity fill out the entire space of possible measures,
 i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lim_{t\rightarrow\infty}\{\beta_{t}\}_{t}\equiv\{P(\bs_{t}|x_{:t})\}_{t}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As for the geometry of this measure,
 it naively lives in an 
\begin_inset Formula $|\mathcal{S}|$
\end_inset

-dimensional space.
 However,
 there might be some low-dimensional manifold:
 suppose the latent transition matrix is structured:
 then,
 as per Shai et al.
 (2024) (I am familiar with the paper,
 but have not re-read it),
 the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\bT^{t}\bm{1}\}_{t}$
\end_inset

 will reflect such structure:
 states 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 that transition to themselves will form clusters,
 whereas rare states will leave holes in the simplex.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In particular,
 I would expect that along context positions,
 latents 
\begin_inset Formula $\log\beta_{t}$
\end_inset

 move according to the incoming evidence,
 meaning that the evidence 
\begin_inset Formula $\log P(x_{t}|\bs{}_{t})$
\end_inset

 is a sort of velocity in latent space (I did not come up with this idea while writing this text,
 John Schwarcz and I had thought along similar lines during 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "our work"
target "https://journals.plos.org/ploscompbiol/article?id=10.1371/journal.pcbi.1013675"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 on belief state updates in LSTMs).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Are there multiple possible geometries you can think of?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I think the number of geometries depends on the number of non-interacting processes that the world environment defines.
 Each such process context 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 will (relatively) quickly be identified by the transformer,
 and its updates will be forwarded independently.
 I'd expect the latter to happen in disjoint subspaces,
 such that the first layer's MLP would need to be expanded as 
\begin_inset Formula $\bW_{\MLP}^{1}\coloneqq\text{diag}\left([\bT^{(c)}]_{c}\right)$
\end_inset

,
 i.e.
 a block-diagonal matrix with each context's transition matrix on the diagonal.
 Recognition of a context could be implemented via 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 multi-head self-attention in layer 0 (one head 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 = one context 
